@albertocon4136 it was to show how a very basic design can create movement using electromagnatism.
Its not such an easy task to place a power line high enough to access the volts needed to power it. 
Tesla built quite a spectacular tower to acheive this voltage suply.

@bugaboo9442 pseudoscience often has real science within, they just horribly distort our best understanding in to complete nonsense quackery.

Imagine if there actually was this near limitless current from potential difference everywhere. All of our electronics would have induced currents running haywire. It would be like unending coronal mass ejections, the 1859 geomagnetic storm but for every second of every day. Bitflips... oh the bitflips.

Luckily in real life even with large potential differences, any amount of current draw floors the voltage. The induced voltages/currents are so small they can be trivially removed by filtering capacitors before processing.

@ThinkingandTinkering I am sorry mate and I don't mean to be rude....but you are the one who claims this type of motor can harness the power of electrostatics in the air....and then you proceed to power the motor yourself using a power supply stepped up to high voltage.  What does that have to do with electrostatic power in the air?
You even say it is a MOTOR.  I agree, it is a motor.  But if your claim of free energy in the air is true, why don't you call it a GENERATOR?
And if you claim it is more than a curiosity why not include just one practical application? Why did you stop at demonstrating that it can spin? Why not just hook up your magical electrostatic power gathering "antenna" and demonstrate that it can do some work.  As far as I can see you have not even demonstrated that it can spin itself without inputting power from a power supply.

@joedee1863 Why?... Corporate Greed crushed the idea the first time round. Since then, we have gained a superpower... Crowdfunding. There is power in numbers.
If only Tesla had not been such a loner. 
He had visions that could have changed  the world for the better. He wanted a better world but only received a bitter one... one that crushed his ideas and kept them from becoming a reality.
